{{Infobox person |name = David S. Muir |image = |caption = |birth_name = |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1971|1|4|df=yes}} |birth_place = [[Falkirk]], [[United Kingdom]] |death_date = |death_place = |other_names = |alma_mater = [[University of Glasgow]] |known_for = Director of Political Strategy for [[Gordon Brown]] |occupation = |nationality = British}}
'''David S. Muir''' (born 4 January 1971) is a [[Scotland|Scottish]] marketing and [[political communications]] professional. He was Director of Political Strategy for [[British prime minister]] [[Gordon Brown]] between 2008 and 2010.
==Biography== Muir was born in Falkirk and attended his local comprehensive [[Falkirk High School]]. In 1988 attended the [[University of Glasgow]]. In 1992 he graduated with a MA Hons 1st Class in Politics and Economics. He also won the Alistair Reid Prize for Politics for the outstanding study of politics and an ESU Scholarship to work with the US politician [[Byron Dorgan]]. He later graduated from [[London Business School]] with a [[Master of Business Administration]].
==Career== In 1992 Muir joined the advertising agency [[Ogilvy & Mather]], becoming New Business Director until taking a leave of absence to complete his MBA in 1999. In 2001 he returned to Ogilvy where he focussed on expanding the group through organic growth and acquisitions. In 2003 he wrote with Jon Miller ''The Business of Brands'', looking at how businesses could nurture and value their brands.
In 2005 he moved over to [[WPP plc|WPP]] to take over "The Channel" from Mandy Pooler.<ref>{{cite web|author=John Tylee |url=http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/news/233834/Muir-takes-Channel/?DCMP=ILC-SEARCH |title=Muir takes over at The Channel - advertising news - Campaign |publisher=Campaignlive.co.uk |date=2005-01-28 |accessdate=2011-05-26}}</ref> There he helped develop WPP's research tool Brandz where he developed the BrandZ Top 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.brandrepublic.com/blogs/ritson_on_brand/archive/2006/03/08/millward-brown-optimors-valuation-of-brands.aspx |title=Millward Brown Optimor's Valuation of Brands - Ritson on Brand - Blogs - Brand Republic |publisher=Community.brandrepublic.com |date= |accessdate=2011-05-26}}</ref> While at The Channel he also developed Sportz<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wpp.com/wpp/press/press/default.htm?guid={1ea68e94-3aec-45c4-b8f8-a4dc6928d17e} |title=sports specialist companies launch global sports brands study: SportZ |publisher=WPP |date=2003-03-11 |accessdate=2011-05-26}}</ref> which allows global brands to evaluate sponsorship opportunities.
===Downing Street=== In 2008 Muir left WPP to become the British prime minister, [[Gordon Brown]]'s, Director of Political Strategy, replacing [[Spencer Livermore]] who had left<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/536926/team-brown-strengthens.thtml |title=Team Brown strengthens |publisher=The Spectator |date= |accessdate=2011-05-26}}</ref> At Downing Street Muir was the Prime Ministers leading political adviser after Stephen Carter left. He along with Kirsty McNeill developed Brown's "No time for a novice speech" at the 2008 Labour Party Conference which was "warmly received".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7630567.stm |title=UK &#124; UK Politics &#124; No time for a novice, says Brown |publisher=BBC News |date=2008-09-23 |accessdate=2011-05-26}}</ref><ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article4813281.ece ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090513035509/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article4813281.ece |date=13 May 2009 }}</ref>
Muir worked closely with [[Peter Mandelson]] and [[Philip Gould]] on the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]'s [[United Kingdom general election, 2010|2010 general election]] campaign. He was the lead negotiator of the historic British TV Election Debates and was an early proponent of them.<ref>[http://wayback.vefsafn.is/wayback/20100418101319/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/election_2010/article7018474.ece ]</ref>
He is believed to have argued for a hard edged attack on the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] and their threat to middle income earners.<ref>{{cite news|author=Patrick Wintour, political editor |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/jul/15/peter-mandelson-memoirs-brown-economy |title=Peter Mandelson on Brown: 'We were in a pit of debt. And we kept on digging' &#124; Politics |publisher=The Guardian |date= 15 July 2010|accessdate=2011-05-26 |location=London}}</ref> In particular he pushed for the campaign to focus on the threat the Conservative's posed to child tax credits. It is also believed that he supported Gordon Brown's decision not to serve a full term.<ref>{{cite news|author=Patrick Wintour, political editor |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/18/gordon-brown-ed-balls-resignation |title=Gordon Brown tried to announce resignation before election &#124; Politics |publisher=The Guardian |date= 18 May 2010|accessdate=2011-05-26 |location=London}}</ref>
The campaign denied the Conservatives an overall majority and Muir was part of small team that spent the next five days in discussions with the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]. Muir left Downing Street when Gordon Brown resigned in May 2010.
